ing while walking behind to anyone walking in front who is not sick this is how you should trainOne should not give a teaching while walking behind to anyone walking in front who is not sickIf a monk out of disrespect gives a teaching while walking behind to someone walking in front who is not sick he commits an offense of wrong conductif it is unintentionalif he is the first offenderThe eleventh training rule is finishedTheravāda Collection on Monastic LawThe monks rules and their analysisThe chapter on trainingThe subchapter on laughing loudlyThe second training rule on swinging the armsAt one time the Buddha was staying at Sāvatthī in the Jeta Grove Anāthapiṇḍikas MonasteryAt that time the monks from the group of six were swinging and dangling their arms while sitting in inhabited areas I will not swing my arms while sitting in inhabited areas this is how you should trainOne should not swing ones arms while sitting in an inhabited areaone should sit keeping ones arms steadyIf a monk out of disrespect swings and dangles his arms while sitting in an inhabited area he commits an offense of wrong conductif he does not knowif he has entered his dwellingif he is insaneif he is the first offenderThe eighth training rule is finishedTheravāda Collection on Monastic LawThe monks rules and their analysisThe chapter on trainingThe subchapter on laughing loudlyThe training rule on loud noisesAt one time the Buddha was staying at Sāvatthī in the Jeta Grove Anāthapiṇḍikas MonasteryAt that time the monks from the group of six were noisy while walking in inhabited areas I will not be noisy while walking in inhabited areas this is how you should trainOne should not be noisy while walking in an inhabited areaIf a monk out of disrespect makes loud noises while walking in an inhabited area he commits an offense of wrong conductif he does not knowif he is insaneif he is the first offenderThe third training rule is finishedTheravāda Collection on Monastic LawThe monks rules and their analysisThe chapter on trainingThe subchapter on slurpingThe training rule on licking the almsbowlAt one time the Buddha was staying at Sāvatthī in the Jeta Grove Anāthapiṇḍikas MonasteryAt that time the monks from the group of six were licking their bowls while eating I will not lick my almsbowl while eating this is how you should trainOne should not lick ones bowl while eatingIf a monk out of disrespect licks his bowl while eating he commits an offense of wrong conductif he does not knowif only a little food remains and he eats it after collecting it in one place and then licking itif he is insaneif he is the first offenderThe third training rule is finishedTheravāda Collection on Monastic LawThe monks rules and their analysisThe chapter on trainingThe subchapter on mouthfulsThe training rule on chompingAt one time the Buddha was staying at Sāvatthī in the Jeta Grove Anāthapiṇḍikas MonasteryAt that time the monks from the group of six made a chomping sound while eating I will not make a chomping sound while eating this is how you should trainOne should not make a chomping sound while eatingIf a monk out of disrespect makes a chomping sound while eating he commits an offense of wrong conductif it is unintentionalif he is the first offenderThe tenth training rule is finishedThe fifth subchapter on mouthfuls is finishedTheravāda Collection on Monastic LawThe monks rules and their analysisThe chapter on trainingThe subchapter on mouthfulsThe training rule on without bringingAt one time the Buddha was staying at Sāvatthī in the Jeta Grove Anāthapiṇḍikas MonasteryAt that time the monks from the group of six opened their mouths without bringing a mouthful to it I will not open my mouth without bringing a mouthful to it this is how you should trainOne should not open ones mouth without bringing a mouthful to itIf a monk out of disrespect opens his mouth without bringing a mouthful to it he commits an offense of wrong conductif it is unintentionalif he is the first offender