Is it true monks that you do thisIts true SirThe Buddha rebuked them Foolish men how can you do thisThis wont give rise to confidence in those without it And monks this training rule should be recited like thisI will wear my sarong evenly all around this is how you should trainOne should wear ones sarong evenly all around covering the navel and the kneesIf a monk out of disrespect wears his sarong hanging down in front or behind he commits an offense of wrong conductif he does not knowif he is insaneif he is the first offenderThe first training rule is finishedTheravāda Collection on Monastic LawThe monks rules and their analysisThe chapter on trainingThe subchapter on slurpingThe training rule on slurpingAt one time the Buddha was staying at Kosambī in Ghositas MonasteryAt that time a brahmin had prepared a milk drink for the SanghaThe monks drank the milk making a slurping soundA monk who was previously an entertainer made a joke of it sayingIts as if the whole sangha were cooledThe monks of few desires complained and criticized himHow can a monk joke about the Sangha Is it true monk that you did thisIts true SirThe Buddha rebuked him Foolish man how can you do thisThis wont give rise to confidence in those without it  and after rebuking him he gave a teaching and addressed the monksMonks you should not joke about the Buddha the Teaching or the SanghaIf you do you commit an offense of wrong conductAfter rebuking that monk in many ways for being difficult to support  the Buddha saidAnd monks this training rule should be recited like thisI will not slurp while eating this is how you should trainOne should not slurp while eatingIf a monk out of disrespect slurps while eating he commits an offense of wrong conductif it is unintentionalif he is the first offenderThe first training rule is finishedTheravāda Collection on Monastic LawThe monks rules and their analysisThe chapter on trainingThe subchapter on evenly all aroundThe second training rule on wellcoveredAt one time the Buddha was staying at Sāvatthī in the Jeta Grove Anāthapiṇḍikas MonasteryAt that time the monks from the group of six were sitting in inhabited areas with their bodies uncovered I will sit wellcovered in inhabited areas this is how you should trainOne should be wellcovered while sitting in an inhabited areaIf a monk out of disrespect sits in an inhabited area with his body uncovered he commits an offense of wrong conductif he does not knowif he has entered his dwellingif he is insaneif he is the first offenderThe fourth training rule is finishedTheravāda Collection on Monastic LawThe monks rules and their analysisThe chapter on trainingThe subchapter on respectfullyThe training rule on asking for rice and bean curryAt one time the Buddha was staying at Sāvatthī in the Jeta Grove Anāthapiṇḍikas MonasteryAt that time the monks from the group of six ate rice and bean curry that they themselves had asked forPeople complained and criticized themHow can the Sakyan ascetics eat rice and bean curry that they themselves have asked forWho doesnt like nice foodWho doesnt prefer tasty foodThe monks heard the complaints of those peopleand the monks of few desires complained and criticized those monksHow can the monks from the group of six do this Is it true monks that you do thisIts true SirThe Buddha rebuked them Foolish men how can you do thisThis wont give rise to confidence in those without it And monks this training rule should be recited like thisI will not ask for bean curry or rice for myself and then eat it this is how you should trainIn this way the Buddha laid down this training rule for the monksSoon afterwards a number of monks were sickThe monks who were looking after them askedWe hope youre bearing up we hope youre getting betterPreviously we ate rice and bean curry that we ourselves had asked for and then we were comfortablethat the Buddha has prohibited this we dont ask because were afraid of wrongdoing And because of that were not comfortableThey told the Buddha Soon afterwards he gave a teaching and addressed the monksMonks I allow a sick monk to eat rice and bean curry that he himself has asked forAnd so monks this training rule should be recited like thisWhen not sick I will not ask for bean curry or rice for myself and then eat it this is how you should trainWhen one is not sick one should not ask for bean curry or rice for oneself and then eat itIf a monk who is not sick out of disrespect eats bean curry or rice that he himself has asked for he commits an offense of wrong conductif he does not knowif it is from those who have given an invitationif it is for the benefit of someone elseif it is by means of his own propertyif he is insaneif he is the first offenderThe seventh training rule is finishedTheravāda Collection on Monastic LawThe monks rules and their analysisThe chapter on trainingThe subchapter on shoesThe training rule on shoesAt one time the Buddha was staying at Sāvatthī in the Jeta Grove Anāthapiṇḍikas MonasteryAt that time the monks from the group of six gave teachings to people wearing shoes I will not give a teaching to anyone wearing shoes who is not sick this is how you should trainOne should not give a teaching to anyone wearing shoes who is not sickIf a monk out of disrespect gives a teaching to someone who is not sick and who is standing on shoes whose shoes are fastened or whose shoes are loose he commits an offense of wrong conductif it is unintentionalif he is the first offenderThe first training rule is finishedTheravāda Collection on Monastic LawThe monks rules and their analysisThe chapter on trainingThe subchapter on mouthfulsThe training rule on lifted balls of foodAt one time the Buddha was staying at Sāvatthī in the Jeta Grove Anāthapiṇḍikas MonasteryAt that time the monks from the group of six ate from lifted balls of food I will not eat from a lifted ball of food this is how you should trainOne should not eat from a lifted ball of foodIf a monk out of disrespect eats from a lifted ball of food he commits an offense of wrong conductif he does not knowif it is any kind of fruitif he is insaneif he is the first offenderThe fourth training rule is finishedTheravāda Collection on Monastic LawThe monks rules and their analysisThe chapter on trainingThe subchapter on mouthfulsThe second training rule on without bringingAt one time the Buddha was staying at Sāvatthī in the Jeta Grove Anāthapiṇḍikas MonasteryAt that time the monks from the group of six put their whole hand in their mouths while eating I will not put my whole hand in my mouth while eating this is how you should trainOne should not put ones whole hand in ones mouth while eatingIf a monk out of disrespect puts his whole hand in his mouth while eating he commits an offense of wrong conductif it is unintentionalif he is the first offenderThe second training rule is finishedTheravāda Collection on Monastic LawThe monks rules and their analysisThe chapter on trainingThe subchapter on arms akimboThe training rule on receiving an even measure of bean curryAt one time the Buddha was staying at Sāvatthī in the Jeta Grove Anāthapiṇḍikas MonasteryAt that time the monks from the group of six were receiving almsfood with large amounts of bean curry I will receive almsfood with the right proportion of bean curry this is how you should trainthere are two kinds of bean curry to be taken with the hand mungbean curry and blackgram curryAlmsfood should be received with the right proportion of bean curryIf a monk out of disrespect receives much bean curry he commits an offense of wrong conductif he does not knowif it is from those who have given an invitationif it is for the benefit of someone elseif it is by means of his own propertyif he is insaneif he is the first offenderThe ninth training rule is finishedTheravāda Collection on Monastic LawThe monks rules and their analysisThe chapter on trainingThe subchapter on laughing loudlyThe second training rule on swaying the headAt one time the Buddha wa