sociation gave the prepared robes to them and served the food to the SanghaThe monks who knew that a meal together with robes had been prepared for the Sangha but who did not know that the robes had been given to those monks from the group six saidYou may offer the robesThere isnt anyThe robes we had prepared were diverted by the monks from the group of six to themselvesThe monks of few desires complained and criticized those monksHow can the monks from the group of six divert to themselves things they know were intended for the SanghaAfter rebuking those monks in many ways they told the Buddha Soon afterwards he had the Sangha gathered and questioned the monksIs it true monks that you did thisIts true SirThe Buddha rebuked them Foolish men how can you divert to yourselves things that you know were intended for the SanghaThis wont give rise to confidence in those without it And monks this training rule should be recited like thisIf a monk diverts to himself material support that he knows was intended for the Sangha he commits an offense entailing relinquishment and confession The monk who has been given the full ordination by a unanimous Sangha through a legal procedure consisting of one motion and three announcements that is irreversible and fit to standthis sort of monk is meant in this casehe knows by himself or others have told him or the donor has told himFor the Sanghagiven to the Sangha given up to the Sangharobes almsfood a dwelling and medicines even a bit of bath powder a toothbrush or a piece of stringthey have said Well give Well prepareIf he diverts it to himself then for the effort there is an act of wrong conductWhen he gets it it becomes subject to relinquishmentIt should be relinquished to a sangha a group or an individualAnd monks it should be relinquished like thisVenerables this thing which I diverted to myself knowing that it was intended for the Sangha is to be relinquishedI relinquish it to the Sangha the Sangha should give you should give I g